                        <p style="text-align:justify">The Dynamic Systems Development Method (DSDM) framework was initially published in 1995 and is administered by the DSDM Consortium.</p>
                        <p style="text-align:justify">DSDM sets quality and effort in terms of cost and time at the outset and adjusts the project deliverables to meet set criteria by prioritizing the deliverables into "Must have", "Should have", "Could have", and "Won't have" categories (using the MoSCoW prioritization technique).</p>
                        <p style="text-align:justify">DSDM is a system-oriented method with six distinct phases: Pre-project; Feasibility; Foundations; Exploration and Engineering; Deployment; and Benefit Assessment.</p>
                        <p style="text-align:justify">A later version of DSDM known as DSDM Atern was introduced in 2007 and focuses on both prioritization of deliverables and consistent user or customer collaboration. The newest version is inspired by an Arctic Tern, making it a developer-centric software development framework for on-time and in-budget delivery of user-valued and quality-controlled project features.</p>
                    </div>
